Chaining ‚Äúthen‚Äù callbacks
The next example is fairly straightforward. Let‚Äôs make sure our promise object is able to chain then functions and transmit return values from callback to callback:

The first expect call is a ‚Äúsmoke‚Äù precaution to avoid weird failures in case we receive something unexpected from the promise. The second expect actually meets our goal, and uses the tweet text to transmit a ‚Äúmodified‚Äù return value through the chain.
You are probably noticing: this is starting to get hairy! Why are we going through all this trouble to test an HTTP promise? Let‚Äôs improve this thing and make our point clearer, starting with some sensible DRY improvements.
Refactoring our test
This is the most entertaining part of the process. Looking at what we currently have, the code to perform an HTTP request is particularly repetitive and annoying.
Let‚Äôs make good use of JavaScript by leveraging its dynamism the right way! Why not extract a helper method to return an ‚Äúextended‚Äù fake server object?

Notice how we are extending the object with a new member function that‚Äôs especially suited for what we need. Now we can apply the helper to all of our examples:

That‚Äôs a bit better, but we can improve it even further with a promise assertion plugin.
Using chai-as-expected to improve promise assertions
In the end, a promise resolves to the value returned by its last callback, right? chai-as-expected allows us to turn this:
return promise.then((body) => {
  expect(body).to.deep.equal(response);
});
Into this:
return expect(promise).to.eventually.equal(response);
How does it work? Chaining the eventually attribute before any existing chai expectation has the effect of ‚Äúpromisifying‚Äù it. Furthermore, mocha automatically waits for returned promises, remember that?
Now let‚Äôs install the plugin as an NPM dev dependency:
npm install chai-as-expected --save-dev
We need to tell chai about this new plugin. Edit spec/javascripts/index.integration.js, so that it looks like this:

Great. Now we can refactor our spec:

Hola! That‚Äôs a bit better and easier to read. Now let‚Äôs tackle the last context of this spec.
When the timeline response is üëé
And what if we eventually get a non-200 HTTP response? Well, the catch callback should be fired with an error object, including at least the HTTP status code and the body.
Fortunately, axios implements that behavior out of the box and our example gets pretty straightforward:

And it passes right away.
For sanity‚Äôs sake, I suggest you to change the expected value and check if anything fails. A spec that passes right on the first run should be faced as a smell, it doesn‚Äôt matter whether testing before or after the implementation!
And we are finally done with fetchTimeline!
But hasn‚Äôt a promise more features than this?
Yeah, a promise has other behaviors. However, that‚Äôs just enough to secure our implementation and provide confidence that it works correctly, taking into account the features we will actually use.
Why is this a good test?
Astute readers will probably ask:
Couldn‚Äôt we have used stubs to test this?
Yes, but that would probably be a bad move. I really like using stubs when it makes sense, but in some cases they couple too much with the implementation and make things harder to change. Focusing on actual behavior is always a better bet.
The advantage of the current approach is that we can switch out the HTTP code to use any promise-compliant library. Now here‚Äôs what‚Äôs downright cool: the following jQuery code has the same behavior and would still make our specs pass:

